                                        <ref target="https://vceditor.library.upenn.edu/project/668514445d69680001453616/viewOnly">Viscoll collation</ref>
                                    </p>
                                    <signatures>Quire signatures in the form of Roman numerals on the verso of the last leaf in a quire (first signature written in letters, <quote>primus</quote>). The signatures are of varying size and sometimes decorated, e.g. <locus from="48v" to="48v" scheme="folios"/>. Occasionally the signatures are also found in the upper left corner on the first leaf of a new quire, e.g. <locus from="137r" to="137r" scheme="folios"/>.</signatures>
                                    <catchwords>Catchwords in brown ink. On <locus from="48v" to="48v" scheme="folios"/> in red ink. On some quires, e.g. <locus from="56v" to="56v" scheme="folios"/>, the catchwords have been lost due to trimming. </catchwords>
                                </collation>
                                <condition>
                                    <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> consist of a fragment from a manuscript over which blank parchment has been pasted. This parchment has been partially torn off and now covers half the text of the underlying fragment. On the upper part of the <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/> there is a small fragment of torn of parchment leaf with text, under this is a stained but otherwise intact parchement leaf.</condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Bottom left corner on the torn upper layer of parchment pastedown, in brown ink: <quote>8 229</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Upper part of the page, in black ink by a modern hand: <quote>Kongl. Bibl.<hi rend="super">t</hi> 1734 års Kat. Theol. in 4<hi rend="super">o</hi> no 4</quote>; centre page: <quote>Commentarius super Matthaeum Latine</quote>; below: <quote>Mscr de fine sec. xii vel principio sec. xiii</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown">
                                <p> Medieval binding. Brown leather over thick wooden boards. 3 double raised bands. On <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, in brown ink on paper label: <quote>Commentarius super Matthaeum N<hi rend="super">o</hi> 4</quote>; stamped in gold: <quote>A 147</quote>; in ink on paper label (pasted over an older label): <quote>e.30.9.21.</quote>; remains of a label with illegible text.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/> are fragments from a Carolingian text, the passio S. Dionysii. Two fragments of the same text have previously been removed from the manuscripts. These fragments are stored separately under the signum National Library, MS A 137a, see this post.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="285" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="195" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="85" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <condition>Leather extremely worn with repairs on upper part of <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>. <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, remains after clasp (holes and two nails). Board attachement visible on <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origDate notAfter="1250" notBefore="1150">12th century, late, or 13th century, early</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Origin and early provenance unknown. In the later Middle Ages the manuscript belonged to the Celestines of <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100268">Marcoussis</placeName>, as indicated by the addition on <locus from="184v" to="184v" scheme="folios"/>. Their monastic library was sacked in the wars of the 16th century. After this the manuscript belonged to <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102544">Paul Petau</persName> and was then acquired from him by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100086">Queen Christina</persName> who brought it to <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100081">Sweden</placeName>. The manuscript has been at the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">Royal Library</orgName> since the 17th century.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The signa found on the manuscript correspond to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), where it is listed as: <quote>Theol in 4o no 4</quote>; and to Hammarsköld’s catalogue from the 19th century (U 133), where it is listed as: <quote>e.30.9.21</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
