                        <msContents>
                            <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="1r" to="184v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102626"> Geoffroy Babion </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Commentary on Matthew</title>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="3v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Prologue</title>
                                    <incipit>DOMINVS ac redemptor noster ad conmendationem et confirmationem euangelice fidei uoluit euuangelium non solum hominibus predicari sed etiam contra hereticam prauitatem scripto retineri </incipit>
                                    <explicit>tum per sacerdotium tum per regnum tum per eius diuinitatem</explicit>
                                </msItem>
                                <msItem>
                                    <locus from="3v" to="184v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <title type="desc">Commentary</title>
                                    <rubric>Genealogia christi Secundum quod homo</rubric>
                                    <incipit>IN IPSE EXORDIO satis ostendit quod de humanitate christi sit acturus</incipit>
                                    <explicit defective="true">Lucas enim et iohannes satis aperte dicunt ipsa die resurrectionis domini uisum esse in iherusalem </explicit>
                                    <note>Last quire missing, based on the owner's signature on <locus from="184v" to="184v" scheme="folios"/> this quire was already missing in the later Middle Ages.</note>
                                    <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107168">PL</title>
                                        <citedRange from="162" to="162" unit="volume"/>
                                        <citedRange from="1227" to="1500" unit="column"/>
                                        <note>In PL the commentary is attributed to Anselm of Laon.</note>
                                    </bibl>
                                </msItem>
                                <note>For a discussion of the authorship see <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107327">Eriksson (1935)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="183" to="185" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                        </msContents>
                        <physDesc>
                            <objectDesc>
                                <supportDesc material="parchment">
                                    <support>
                                        <p>
                                            <locus from="1r" to="184v" scheme="folios"/>
                                            <material>Parchment</material>
                                            <dimensions type="leaf">
                                                <height quantity="275" unit="mm"/>
                                                <width quantity="180" unit="mm"/>
                                            </dimensions>
                                        </p>
                                    </support>
                                    <extent>
                                        <measure type="textblockLeaves" quantity="184" unit="folios"/>
                                    </extent>
                                    <condition>The parchment is fairly rough, the leaves are uneven, some with holes (no loss of text), and some with contemporary repairs, e.g. <locus from="41" to="41" scheme="folios"/>. Leaves are dirty and stained in places, in some places damaged by spills with resulting smudging of the ink, e.g. <locus from="3r" to="3r" scheme="folios"/>. Cuts and cut out portions of parchment, e.g. <locus from="8" to="23" scheme="folios"/> (where a small square hole has been cut out in the margin). <locus from="20" to="20" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="137" to="137" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="154" to="154" scheme="folios"/>, and <locus from="168" to="168" scheme="folios"/> strips of parchment cut out and tied into a knot. Words and lines of text erased here and there, eg. <locus from="61v" to="61v" scheme="folios"/>. <locus from="167" to="168" scheme="folios"/>, circular knife or drypoint marks in the outer margin.</condition>
                                </supportDesc>
                                <layoutDesc>
                                    <layout columns="1" ruledLines="36">
                                        <dimensions type="written">
                                            <height quantity="215" unit="mm"/>
                                            <width quantity="125" unit="mm"/>
                                        </dimensions>
                                        <note>Ruling and guidelines in lead. Pricking (sometimes slashing) in the outer and inner margins. On some leaves, e.g. <locus from="45" to="45" scheme="folios"/>, the prickings have been encircled in brown ink. On some leaves, e.g. <locus from="177" to="177" scheme="folios"/> the pricking is slanting.</note>
                                    </layout>
                                </layoutDesc>
                            </objectDesc>
                            <handDesc>
                                <p>The text has been written by several pregothic hands. The hands change at random intervalls and some hands are only responsible for short passages. The hands and the script have been analysed in <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107327">Eriksson (1935)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="180" to="182" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>.</p>
                            </handDesc>
                            <additions>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Upper part of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Comentarius Super Matthaeum</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="2r" to="184v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Marginal and interlinear additions throughout by several medieval hands. The additions consist mainly of corrections and additions of omitted text, e.g. on <locus from="25r" to="25r" scheme="folios"/>. There are also nota marks and simple drawings/doodles in ink the margins, e.g. <locus from="40r" to="40r" scheme="folios"/>. In addition, there are simple drawings in lead point in the margins througout the manuscript, e.g. on <locus from="57v" to="57v" scheme="folios"/> and extensively on <locus from="96r" to="96r" scheme="folios"/>.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="134v" to="135r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>A small paper fragment is placed between these leaves. The fragment contains text on both sides, but seems to have been used as a bookmark.</note>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <locus from="184v" to="184v" scheme="folios"/>
                                    <note>Bottom of page, in black ink by a medieval hand: <quote>Liber iste est de conuentu celestinorum sancti trinitatis de marcossiaco</quote>.</note>
                                </p>
                            </additions>
                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in brown and black ink, capitals touched in red. The ascenders on the top line and the descenders on the bottom line are often elongated, and sometimes decorated or decorated with flourishing, e.g. <locus from="13r" to="13r" scheme="folios"/> and <locus from="15v" to="15v" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                                <decoNote type="initials">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>: Opening penwork D over 5 lines (and extending above the line) in red. <locus from="3v" to="3v" scheme="folios"/>: penwork I over 8 lines (and extending below the line) in red. <locus from="163v" to="163v" scheme="folios"/>: penwork S over 8 lines (and extending into the margin) in red. In general, the decoration of the manuscript gives an impression of improvisation or randomness. Besides the three larger initials there are several other types of initials used, but no discernable pattern to their use. Some chapters are introduced by penwork initials in red, e.g. <locus from="17r" to="17r" scheme="folios"/>, others by plain initials in black with red flourishing, e.g. <locus from="142v" to="142v" scheme="folios"/>. There are also a type of initial in black and red, e.g. on <locus from="15r" to="15r" scheme="folios"/>, which are close to in style to the smaller capitals. On <locus from="40v" to="45v" scheme="folios"/> such intitials are used frequently.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                            </decoDesc>
                        </physDesc>
